# Implementation Guidelines

This document describes the implementation guidelines that must be followed in this project.

## Project structure

- `features/` directory contains feature files organized in a feature based way
- `mock/netlify/functions/datafile.json` contains a Mockoon API mock definition
- `src/app/` directory contains all pages of the app organized by Next.JS documentation
- `src/app/<page-name>/components/` directory contains all React components that are used only on that page
- `src/components/` directory contains shared components that are used across multiple features

The project also contains the following important packages.

- `@eduriam/ui-core` - a component library used by this project
- `@eduriam/ui-x` - a library of more complex components for this project

## Conventions and best practices

### Component usage and implementation

When using or creating a new component:

1. Always use @eduriam/ui-core and @eduriam/ui-x components if available
2. If the component is not available and is only used by the given page (feature), implement it in the components directory of that page
3. If the component is not available and is used by multiple pages (feature), implement it in the `src/components/` directory

#### Component structure

Each component implemented in this project should be in a separate folder named in PascalCase.

The component folder should have the following structure:

- `<Name>.tsx`: component implementation
- `<Name>.stories.tsx`: Storybook stories with interaction tests

## Code

### Top Navigation Bars

If you want to include a navigation bar for your page, put it into the "page" file. You can use the following reusable navigation bars:

- BackNavigationBar - simple navigation bar with a back button
- ProgressNavbar - simple navigation bar with a progress indicator and one icon button (from @eduriam/ui-core)

Or you can create your own page specific navigation bar. To do that, just use the BasicNavigationBar (from @eduriam/ui-core) and customize it via props. If you need a fully custom navigation bar, you can create it as a separate component in the given page folder.

### Page Transitions

Use `useTransitionNavigationHandler()` for transition-aware navigation:

- `navigateWithTransition("/path")` for forward slide
- `navigateWithTransition("/path", { direction: "back" })` for back slide
